            "description": "<p>On a moonlit night some 2,500 years ago, Sakyamuni passed away. His teachings formed the basis of Buddhism, and as he lay dying— on a couch in the Himalayan foothills— a golden light emanated from his face. It reached every corner of the world, calling even his most far-flung followers to his deathbed. Sakyamuni had instructed his followers not to grieve his death. He had, after all, achieved the state of Nirvana during his life on earth; in dying, he would be freed from the endless cycle of rebirth and suffering. He would attain Parinirvana, a state of perfect bliss with no death and no earthly body. </p>",
