            "id": "10436",
            "meta1": "Claude Monet (French, 1840–1926)",
            "meta2": "",
            "meta3": "",
            "thumbnail": "http://api.artsmia.org/images/10436/large.jpg",
            "description": "<p>What happens to light when summer turns to autumn, the moon rises, or a soft snow falls? Monet found the answers, painting the same familiar scene near his home in Giverny in all seasons, at all hours, in all kinds of weather. A grainstack sits broadly in a field, the edges of its silhouette glowing as the sun climbs amid a cool mist to illuminate the landscape. Orange, yellow, green, and violet dance across the field as the earth meets the sky in a hazy blur. For Monet, this light was just as much the subject of his work as the grainstack itself.</p>",
