                            "title": "Bouncing Babies",
                            "description": "<p>Pre-printed patterns for embroidery, usually done in red, were called redwork or penny squares, a reference to their typical cost in shops. But women could also find redwork patterns in magazines like <em>The Ladies’ Home Journal and Godey’s Lady’s Book</em>, which published patterns, listed ads for patterns, and gave away pattern kits as incentives to subscribe. Quilt-makers often combined images from several sources in a single quilt, and it’s possible that the baby patterns seen here were not purchased at the exposition.</p>"
