            "id": "64094",
            "description": "<p>This souvenir of the 1901 Pan-American Exposition, a kind of World’s Fair meant to showcase American progress, required a bit more work than a postcard. Each square of this quilt top was likely purchased separately, in kits sold for a penny, and had to be sewn together. That said, the quirky mix of designs—exhibition pavilions, historical/political figures, children, birds, plants, sayings—were probably pre-printed on the fabric. All the embroiderer had to do was follow the lines.</p>",
