            "id": "94341",
            "description": "<p>A quilt is a three-part sandwich. The top is where most of the drama happens, where the designs and details are most prominent. The middle is the meat, made of batting—the fluffy stuff that gives a quilt its heft. The thicker the batting, the warmer you'll be underneath it. (In the past, the middle consisted of another layer of fabric, or even paper.) Then there's the backing, usually less decorative than the top. The final step: quilting stitches, which add another subtle element of design and join all three layers together. </p>",
